yes, but before you need to define those font-names with files containig actual font. Something like this:



font-family: 'QuicksandBook';

    src: url('Quicksand_Book-webfont.eot');

    src: url('Quicksand_Book-webfont.eot?#iefix') format('embedded-opentype'),

        url('Quicksand_Book-webfont.woff') format('woff'),

        url('Quicksand_Book-webfont.ttf') format('truetype'),

        url('Quicksand_Book-webfont.svg#QuicksandLight') format('svg');





then you can apply it for a div:



div {

    font-family: 'QuicksandBook', Arial, sans-serif;

}

Ok, did some experiments and got the typekit webfonts working. Probably, the best thing to do thinking about upgrades, is to make a completely new theme and install it, but, in lieu of that (because I don't know how), I found small changes can be made by editing the files. 



In: 

octopress/source/_includes/custom/head.html



    <script type="text/javascript">

      (function() {

        var config = {

