Hi - this was odd, but, I got it working. Here's what I did - 



* added various font extensions to the .gitattributes, so we can be sure they are not getting damaged by something git is doing, as with the image files

* generated a font "kit" from http://www.fontsquirrel.com/tools/webfont-generator - where, you upload the OTF file you have a license for, and this service converts it to various other types of font file, that work in various browsers, like, .eot, .ttf, .svg.

* added the font files the webfont-generator created to source/assets/font, and edited the css to be like the sample provided, except, changed the path (I'll attach what the site created)



in fonts.scss - 



    @font-face {

        font-family: 'source-code-pro';

        src: url('/assets/font/sourcecodepro-regular-webfont.eot');

        src: url('/assets/font/sourcecodepro-regular-webfont.eot?#iefix') format('embedded-opentype'),

             url('/assets/font/sourcecodepro-regular-webfont.woff') format('woff'),

             url('/assets/font/sourcecodepro-regular-webfont.ttf') format('truetype'),

             url('/assets/font/sourcecodepro-regular-webfont.svg#source_code_proregular') format('svg');

        font-weight: normal;

        font-style: normal;



    }



    @font-face {

        font-family: 'source-code-probold';

        src: url('/assets/font/sourcecodepro-bold-webfont.eot');

        src: url('/assets/font/sourcecodepro-bold-webfont.eot?#iefix') format('embedded-opentype'),

             url('/assets/font/sourcecodepro-bold-webfont.woff') format('woff'),

             url('/assets/font/sourcecodepro-bold-webfont.ttf') format('truetype'),

             url('/assets/font/sourcecodepro-bold-webfont.svg#source_code_probold') format('svg');

        font-weight: normal;

        font-style: normal;



    }



Now it is displaying correctly on that sample blog post.
